{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 20:22:45.679078", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall network health: Good. L3 reachability, OSPF routing, DNS resolution, and HTTP access to the server farm function as expected from multiple user subnets.\n- Load-balancer path and backend isolation: Correct. Clients reach web99.local via 10.200.0.7; backend servers on 20.200.0.0/24 are only reachable by the load balancer and not routable from user subnets, which matches the design.\n- Notable anomaly: Intermittent slow time-to-first-byte (TTFB) to web0.local (and occasionally web1.local) seen from clients, suggesting application/server-side slowness rather than a network issue.\n\nEnd-to-end reachability findings\n- ICMP between user hosts and server farm (10.200.0.0/24): Successful with low RTT and no loss (e.g., host_1_1_1_1 to web_server_2: ~3.6 ms avg; tool-wide ping matrix shows 0% loss).\n- DNS name resolution on hosts:\n  - web0.local -> 10.200.0.3\n  - web99.local -> 10.200.0.7\n  - web1.local -> 10.200.0.4, web2.local -> 10.200.0.5, web3.local -> 10.200.0.6\n- HTTP access from multiple user hosts:\n  - web99.local (load balancer): total times ~1.0–1.3 s, starttransfer ~0.2–0.5 s\n  - web0.local: occasional slower runs with starttransfer ~1.23–1.31 s and total ~2.0–2.1 s; other runs ~1.0–1.3 s\n  - web1.local: mixed; one slower run (connect ~1.03 s, total ~3.05 s), others ~2.2 s\n  - web2.local, web3.local: generally ~1.0–1.25 s\n- Backend isolation observed from clients:\n  - Pings to 20.200.0.1/20.200.0.2 from hosts fail with “Destination Net Unreachable” from distribution routers, consistent with non-advertised backend network.\n\nRouting/OSPF state\n- router_dist_1_1: Sees server VLAN 10.200.0.0/24 via OSPF (cost 40) via 172.16.0.6; 10.1.1.0/24 local; other access subnets learned via OSPF. No 20.200.0.0/24 route present (expected).\n- router_core_1: Correct OSPF routes to access subnets and 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.3; multiple core links up; ECMP where applicable.\n- server_access_router: 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected (br0); distributes it in OSPF to core. No advertisement of 20.200.0.0/24 (expected).\n- Global observation: OSPF adjacencies appear stable from routing tables; end-to-end paths consistent and symmetric.\n\nLoad balancer and backend segment\n- Load balancer (10.200.0.7 on eth0; 20.200.0.1 on eth1):\n  - Nginx active (running).\n  - Upstream config targets backend web servers 20.200.0.2:80, 20.200.0.3:80, 20.200.0.4:80.\n  - Load balancer can ARP and ping all backends successfully (RTT ~0.7 ms).\n  - Default route via 10.200.0.1 ensures return path to client networks.\n- Isolation:\n  - server_access_router does not route/advertise 20.200.0.0/24.\n  - Clients cannot reach 20.200.0.0/24; distribution routers return ICMP Net Unreachable. This matches the design goal that backends are only accessible by the LB.\n\nDNS and DHCP\n- DNS: Local names resolve correctly from clients (getent confirms A records for web0–web3 and web99); DNS server reachable (ICMP ~4.5 ms avg).\n- DHCP: Hosts have valid IPs in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24; reachability to DHCP server is good (e.g., dhcp_server to host pings OK). No evidence of addressing or relay issues.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Performance anomaly: Elevated TTFB for web0.local, and one notable slow run for web1.local from host_1_1_1_1.\n  - Evidence:\n    - web0.local: starttransfer ~1.23–1.31 s and total ~2.0–2.1 s on some runs; other hosts show similar occasional increases.\n    - web1.local: one run showed connect ~1.03 s and total ~3.05 s.\n    - By contrast, web2.local and web3.local generally show starttransfer ~0.24–0.44 s and total ~1.0–1.25 s.\n  - Network counters:\n    - ICMP RTTs are consistently low and no loss; TCP connect times usually low except the single slow web1 run, suggesting server-side (application/content) processing delays rather than network congestion or loss.\n- No routing anomalies: OSPF tables are coherent, next-hops correct, and end-to-end connectivity intact.\n- Backend access control: Working as designed; client attempts to 20.200.0.0/24 are blocked by lack of routes.\n\nFault localization and likely root cause\n- Faulty component(s): Not a network device. The network path (hosts → dist → core → server_access_router → web servers) is healthy.\n- Localized issue: Application or host-level slowness on web_server_0 (and sporadically web_server_1) causing higher TTFB. Load balancer path and backend segment show normal latency and availability; DNS and routing are normal.\n- Root cause hypothesis: Server-side processing delay on web_server_0 (and intermittently web_server_1). There is no evidence of L3 routing faults, DNS mis-resolution, path MTU issues, or transport problems.\n\nConclusion\n- The network is operating correctly: OSPF distribution, server farm reachability, DNS resolution, and load balancer behavior (including backend isolation) align with design intent.\n- The only abnormal behavior observed is intermittent higher application response time on specific web servers (not attributable to the network).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 15623, "output_tokens": 4879, "total_tokens": 20502, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 15488}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3456}}}
